After the first ticket is pulled
out and the winner

5
00:00:07,790 --> 00:00:11,100
determined, the ticket is
taped to the prize.

6
00:00:11,100 --> 00:00:14,070
The next ticket is pulled out to
determine the winner of the

7
00:00:14,070 --> 00:00:15,560
second prize.

8
00:00:15,560 --> 00:00:18,660
Are the two events
independent?

9
00:00:18,660 --> 00:00:19,890
Explain.

10
00:00:19,890 --> 00:00:22,480
Now before we even think about
this exact case, let's think

11
00:00:22,480 --> 00:00:25,040
about what it means for events
to be independent.

12
00:00:25,040 --> 00:00:28,980
It means that the outcome of one
event doesn't affect the

13
00:00:28,980 --> 00:00:31,220
outcome of the other event.

14
00:00:31,220 --> 00:00:35,040
Now in this situation, the first
event-- after the first

15
00:00:35,040 --> 00:00:37,650
ticket is pulled out and the
winner determined-- the ticket

16
00:00:37,650 --> 00:00:41,410
is taped to the prize.

17
00:00:41,410 --> 00:00:43,990
Then the next ticket is pulled
out to determine the winner of

18
00:00:43,990 --> 00:00:45,360
the second prize.

19
00:00:45,360 --> 00:00:48,490
Now, the winner of the second
prize-- the possible winners,

20
00:00:48,490 --> 00:00:53,220
the possible outcomes for the
second prize, is dependent on

21
00:00:53,220 --> 00:00:55,890
who was pulled out for
the first prize.

22
00:00:55,890 --> 00:01:00,300
You can imagine if there's
three tickets, let's say

23
